- - - ( Promises ) - - -

- a promise in JS is something like in real life in 
  where you're committed on something, & it has 2 results,
  either its Completed( resolved ) or Failed( rejected )
  
- Description of Promise( in order ):
• Promise is a constructor function in JavaScript
• Promise is responsible for returning the values of resolve() & reject()
• You create a promise by calling or assigning new Promise(executor)
• The executor is just any function but only takes 2 parameters: resolve and reject,
  it is responsible for calling resolve() & reject()
  ( the 1st param = resolve | the 2nd param = reject ) 


( Example ):

let p = new Promise( 

 function( resolve, reject ) => { 
  let a = 1 + 1 

  if( a == 2 ){ resolve('Success'); }
  else{ reject('Failed'); }
 };

);



**( Resolve & Reject ):

- resolve & reject are callback functions, with the sole purpose of
  passing their value to .then() or .catch() respectively.


( Example ):

- Values or Reasons that can be passed inside Reject & Resolve
  ( both example values can be used in Reject & Resolve )

• resolve(42);                   // Number
• reject("Hello");               // String
• resolve(true);                 // Boolean
• reject(null);                  // null
• resolve(undefined);            // undefined
• reject([1, 2, 3]);             // Array
• resolve({ a: 1, b: 2 });       // Object
• reject(() => "Hi");            // Function
• resolve(new Date());           // Date object
• reject(Promise.resolve(99));   // Another Promise (will auto-flatten)



**( .then & .catch ):

- are Functions whose sole purpose is to receive 
  the value / reason passed by reject & resolve 

- Just like the Promise constructor takes one function with two parameters,
  .then() and .catch(), each, only takes 1 Function w/ only 1 Parameter
  ( their parameter catches the value passed by resolve & reject )

• Resolve .then( (result) => console.log(result) )
• Reject  .catch( (result) => console.log(result) );

( Example ):

let your_ex = "I miss you";
let wifi_signal = "Strong";


let message = new Promise(  
    
( resolve, reject ) => {   
     if( wifi_signal === "Strong" ){ resolve(your_ex); } 
     else{ reject("wifi signal: weak"); }
 }    
    
).then( (result) => console.log(result) )
.catch( (result) => console.log(result) );
// Outputs: "I miss you"



** ( Make Promise more readable ):

function myExecutor(resolve, reject) {
  if (true) { resolve("Success!"); } 
  else { reject("Error!"); }
}

let x = new Promise(myExecutor);

x.then(result => {
  console.log(result);
}).catch(error => {
  console.error(error);
});